{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1d436c5f-7e59-4019-b3c9-2be57ee32108","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` inside the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n$env:PATH += \";$env:USERPROFILE\\.dotnet\\tools\"\n```\n\n**3. Find your process and collect:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps                        # get the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\nThen open the `.speedscope.json` at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails (no SDK in the container), you can sidecar a debug container or download the standalone `dotnet-trace` binary. Alternatively, use `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first for a quick live view of CPU, GC, and threadpool metrics before committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6492fefd-4c81-4137-aab2-fb90e2e9ab4a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request. I should provide concise, actionable steps.","outputTokens":440},"id":"7d54dde6-e4b7-48f5-8035-7c8624309213","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:44:12.649Z","parentId":"db88885f-8f4d-4719-93f6-5f9afe331219"}
